    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1981-12-03T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1981-12-03T20:00:00-05:00" n="111"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <head>111. Telegram From the Department of State to the Embassy in the Soviet
                        Union<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d111fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Central Foreign Policy File, [no film number]. Secret; Immediate; <gloss
                            target="#t_Nodis_1">Nodis</gloss>. Sent Immediate for information to
                        Madrid for US Delegation to <gloss target="#t_CSCE_1">CSCE</gloss>. Sent for
                        information to the Secretary of State’s Delegation. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJ_1">Schumaker</persName> (EUR/SOV/SOBI); cleared by
                            <persName corresp="#p_STW_1">Simons</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJD_1">Scanlan</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_MCE_1"
                            >McManaway</persName>; approved by <persName corresp="#p_SWJ_1"
                            >Stoessel</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName> was
                        in St. Lucia December 2–4 for a meeting of the <gloss target="#t_OAS_1"
                            >OAS</gloss> General Assembly.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1981-12-04T01:00:00+00:00">December 4, 1981, 0100Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>320904/TOSEC 140040. Subject: U.S. Demarche to Soviets on <persName
                        corresp="#p_SA_1">Sakharov</persName>. Ref: State 316836.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d111fn2">See <ref target="#d107">Document 107</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. (S—Entire text).</p>
                <p>2. Soviet <gloss target="#t_DCM_1">DCM</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_BA_1">Bessmertnykh</persName> called <gloss
                        target="#t_DAS_1">DAS</gloss>
                    <persName corresp="#p_SJD_1">Scanlan</persName> on December 3 and said that he
                    wanted to pass on to us orally a reply the Soviet Embassy had just received from
                    Moscow to Undersecretary <persName corresp="#p_SWJ_1">Stoessel</persName>’s
                    demarche to <persName corresp="#p_BA_1">Bessmertnykh</persName> on November 27
                    about “two Soviet gentlemen.” <persName corresp="#p_BA_1"
                        >Bessmertnykh</persName> said that Moscow was surprised that this issue had
                    been raised again after Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_DA_2"
                        >Dobrynin</persName> had presented the official Soviet position to Secretary
                        <persName corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_BA_1"
                        >Bessmertnykh</persName> said he had been instructed to emphasize that there
                    is no such issue in Soviet/American relations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SWJ_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Stoessel</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
